[{"location":"api/#API","page":"API","title":"API","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"api/#Objective-functions","page":"API","title":"Objective functions","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"api/","page":"API","title":"API","text":"AbstractPortfolioOptimiser\nport_variance\nport_return\nsharpe_ratio\nL2_reg\nquadratic_utility\nsemi_ret\ntransaction_cost\nex_ante_tracking_error\nex_post_tracking_error\nlogarithmic_barrier\nkelly_objective","category":"page"},{"location":"api/#PortfolioOptimiser.AbstractPortfolioOptimiser","page":"API","title":"PortfolioOptimiser.AbstractPortfolioOptimiser","text":"Abstract type for subtyping concrete portfolio optimiser structures.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"api/#PortfolioOptimiser.port_variance","page":"API","title":"PortfolioOptimiser.port_variance","text":"port_variance(w, cov_mtx)\n\nComputes the overall portfolio variance according to the weights w, and covariance matrix cov_mtx.\n\nThe portfolio variance sigma^2, is defined as:\n\nsigma^2 = bmw^T Sigma bmw\n\nwhere sigma is the overall portfolio standard deviation, ^T the transpose operator, w the weights, and Sigma the covariance matrix.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"api/#PortfolioOptimiser.port_return","page":"API","title":"PortfolioOptimiser.port_return","text":"port_return(w, mean_ret)\n\nComputes the overall portfolio return according to the weights w, and mean returns mean_ret.\n\nThe portfolio return mu, is defined as:\n\nmu = bmw cdot bmE\n\nwhere bmw are the weights, and bmE the mean returns.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"api/#PortfolioOptimiser.sharpe_ratio","page":"API","title":"PortfolioOptimiser.sharpe_ratio","text":"sharpe_ratio(w, mean_ret, cov_mtx, rf::Real = 0.02)\n\nComputes the portfolio's Sharpe ratio given the weights w, mean returns mean_ret, covariance matrix cov_mtx, and risk free rate rf.\n\nsharpe_ratio(μ, σ, rf::Real = 0.02)\n\nComputes the Sharpe ratio given the return μ, standard deviation σ, and risk free rate rf.\n\nThe Sharpe ratio s, is defined as:\n\ns = dfracmu - rsigma\n\nwhere mu the portfolio's return (see port_return), and sigma the portfolio's standard deviation (see port_variance). Generally speaking, the greater the Sharpe ratio the better the portfolio. \n\nnote: Note\nThe Sharpe ratio penalises large swings in both directions, so assets that tend to have large increases in value are disproportionally penalised by this measure. The Sortino ratio has the same formula but uses an adjusted covariance matrix that accounts only for the negative fluctuations in value. SemiVar() and ExpSemiVar() in AbstractRiskModel implement this adjustment on the covariance matrix. The Mean-Semivariance portfolios in AbstractMeanSemiVar use it in their optimisations.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"api/#PortfolioOptimiser.L2_reg","page":"API","title":"PortfolioOptimiser.L2_reg","text":"L2_reg(w, γ = 1)\n\nL2 regularisation. Minimising this reduces the number of negligible weights w, with a tuning parameter γ. Increasing γ will decrease the number of negligible weights.\n\nThe L_2 regularisation is defined as:\n\nL_2 = gamma Vert bmw Vert\n\nwhere gamma is the tuning parameter, and w the weights.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"api/#PortfolioOptimiser.quadratic_utility","page":"API","title":"PortfolioOptimiser.quadratic_utility","text":"quadratic_utility(w, mean_ret, cov_mtx, risk_aversion = 1)\n\nCalculates the quadratic utility given the weights w, mean returns mean_ret, covariance matrix cov_mtx and risk aversion risk_aversion. Increasing risk_aversion decreases risk. \n\nThe quadratic utility Q, is defined as:\n\nQ = mu - dfrac12 delta  bmw^T Sigma bmw\n\nwhere mu is the overall portfolio expected return (see port_return), delta the risk aversion, w the weights, and Sigma the covariance matrix.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"api/#PortfolioOptimiser.semi_ret","page":"API","title":"PortfolioOptimiser.semi_ret","text":"semi_ret(returns, benchmark = 0)\n\nCompute the historical semi-returns from historical returns, for a given benchmark. Return values greater than benchmark are \"upside\" returns, values lower than benchmark are \"downside\" returns. Each column of returns corresponds to an asset.\n\nHistorical semi returns mathrmR_b, are defined as:\n\nmathrmR_b = dfracmathrmR - bsqrtN\n\nwhere mathrmR are historical returns, b is the benchmark, and N is the number of historical entries (not the number of assets). \n\nnote: Note\nThe value of benchmark should correspond to the frequency of historical returns, i.e. if using daily returns, benchmark should be a reasonable value for daily returns.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"api/#PortfolioOptimiser.transaction_cost","page":"API","title":"PortfolioOptimiser.transaction_cost","text":"transaction_cost(w, w_prev, k = 0.001)\n\nSimple transaction cost model. Sums all the absolute changes in weight and multiplies by a constant k. Simulates a fixed percentage commision from a broker.\n\nThe transacion cost C, is defined as:\n\nC = k lvert bmw - bmw_mathrmprev rvert\n\nwarning: Warning\nAs of JuMP 1.0 there is no support for norm in objective functions. A model wishing to add this to their objective function should instead add it as a Vector Cone constraint, eg:n = length(tickers)\nprev_weights = fill(1 / n), n))\nk = 0.001\n\nextra_vars = [:(z[1:($n)])]\nextra_constraints =\n    [:([$k * (model[:w] - $prev_weights); model[:z]] in MOI.NormOneCone($(n + n)))]\n\nef = EfficientFrontier(tickers, mu, S;\n        extra_vars = extra_vars,\n        extra_constraints = extra_constraints,\n    )Similarly L2-norms must be turned into constraints of type MOI.NormTwoCone. More information on how to do this can be found in JuMP Vector Cones.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"api/#PortfolioOptimiser.ex_ante_tracking_error","page":"API","title":"PortfolioOptimiser.ex_ante_tracking_error","text":"ex_ante_tracking_error(w, cov_mtx, w_bmk)\n\nCompute the square of the ex-ante tracking error from the weights w, covariance matrix cov_mtx, and benchamark weights w_bmk.\n\nThe ex-ante tracking error mathrmErr, is defined as:\n\nmathrmErr = (bmw - bmw_b)^T  Sigma  (bmw - bmw_b)\n\nwhere bmw are the weights, bmw_b the benchmark weights, and Sigma the covariance matrix.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"api/#PortfolioOptimiser.ex_post_tracking_error","page":"API","title":"PortfolioOptimiser.ex_post_tracking_error","text":"ex_post_tracking_error(w, returns, ret_bmk)\n\nCompute the square of the ex-post tracking error from the weights w, historical returns returns, and benchmark returns ret_bmk.\n\nThe ex-post tracking error mathrmErr, is defined as:\n\nbeginaligned\n    bmx = mathrmR bmw - bmR_b  \n    mu = dfrac1N sumlimits_i=1^N x_i \n    mathrmErr = (bmx - mu) cdot (bmx - mu) = Var(r - r_b)\nendaligned\n\nwhere w are the weights, mathrmR historical returns, bmR_b benchmark historical returns. In other words the ex-post tracking error is the variance of the historical returns r, minus the benchmark returns r_b, of the portfolio.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"api/#PortfolioOptimiser.logarithmic_barrier","page":"API","title":"PortfolioOptimiser.logarithmic_barrier","text":"logarithmic_barrier(w, cov_mtx, k = 0.1)\n\nCompute the logarithmic barrier adjusted by k, from the weights w, and covariance matrix cov_mtx.\n\nThe logarithmic barrier L, is defined as:\n\nL = bmw^T Sigma bmw - k sumlimits_i ln( w_i )\n\nwhere sigma^2 = bmw^T Sigma bmw (see port_variance), k the adjustment constant, and w_i the weight of the i'th asset.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"api/#PortfolioOptimiser.kelly_objective","page":"API","title":"PortfolioOptimiser.kelly_objective","text":"kelly_objective(w, mean_ret, cov_mtx, k = 3)\n\nCompute a Kelly objective from adjusted by k, from the weights w, mean returns mean_ret, and covariance matrix cov_mtx.\n\nThe Kelly objective K, is defined as:\n\nK = bmw^T Sigma bmw - dfrac12 k bmw cdot bmE \n\nwhere sigma^2 = bmw^T Sigma bmw (see port_variance), k is the adjustment constant, bmw the weights, and bmE the mean returns.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"api/#Expected-returns","page":"API","title":"Expected returns","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"api/#Risk-models","page":"API","title":"Risk models","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"api/#Efficient-Frontier","page":"API","title":"Efficient Frontier","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"api/#Mean-var","page":"API","title":"Mean-var","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"api/#Mean-semivar","page":"API","title":"Mean-semivar","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"api/#Critical-Value-at-Risk-(CVaR)","page":"API","title":"Critical Value at Risk (CVaR)","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"api/#Critical-Drawdown-at-Risk-(CDaR)","page":"API","title":"Critical Drawdown at Risk (CDaR)","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"api/#Hierarchical-portfolio","page":"API","title":"Hierarchical portfolio","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"api/#Black-Litterman","page":"API","title":"Black-Litterman","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"api/#Critical-line-algorithm","page":"API","title":"Critical line algorithm","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"api/#Asset-allocation","page":"API","title":"Asset allocation","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"api/","page":"API","title":"API","text":"AbstractAllocation\nAllocation{T1,T2,T3}\nAllocation(\n    type::AbstractAllocation,\n    portfolio::AbstractPortfolioOptimiser,\n    latest_prices::AbstractVector;\n    investment = 1e4,\n    rounding = 1,\n    reinvest = false,\n    short_ratio = nothing,\n    optimiser = HiGHS.Optimizer,\n    silent = true,\n)\nroundmult","category":"page"},{"location":"api/#PortfolioOptimiser.AbstractAllocation","page":"API","title":"PortfolioOptimiser.AbstractAllocation","text":"abstract type AbstractAllocation end\nstruct Lazy <: AbstractAllocation end\nstruct Greedy <: AbstractAllocation end\nstruct LP <: AbstractAllocation end\n\nTypes for allocation dispatch.\n\nLazy: Lazy allocation algorithm. Can do fractional shares.\nGreedy: Greedy allocation algorithm. Can do fractional shares.\nLP: Mixed linear integer programming algorithm. Can only handle full shares.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"api/#PortfolioOptimiser.Allocation","page":"API","title":"PortfolioOptimiser.Allocation","text":"struct Allocation{T1,T2,T3}\n    tickers::T1\n    weights::T2\n    shares::T3\nend\n\nConcrete allocation created by Allocation.\n\ntickers: list of tickers.\nweights: list of corresponding weights according to share allocation and latest prices.\nshares: list of corresponding shares according to their optimal allocation.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"api/#PortfolioOptimiser.Allocation-Tuple{AbstractAllocation, AbstractPortfolioOptimiser, AbstractVector}","page":"API","title":"PortfolioOptimiser.Allocation","text":"Allocation(\n    type::AbstractAllocation,\n    portfolio::AbstractPortfolioOptimiser,\n    latest_prices::AbstractVector;\n    investment = 1e4,\n    rounding = 1,\n    reinvest = false,\n    short_ratio = nothing,\n    optimiser = HiGHS.Optimizer,\n    silent = true,\n)\n\nReturns a tuple of an Allocation structure and remaining money after allocating assets.\n\nnote: Note\nShort positions have negative weights and shares.\n\ntype: Allocation algorithm to use, can be Lazy(), Greedy() or LP() (see AbstractAllocation).\nportfolio: Portfolio AbstractPortfolioOptimiser.\nlatest_prices: Vector of latest prices, entries should be in the same order as portfolio.tickers.\ninvestment: value to be invested in the portfolio.\nrounding: Greedy() and Lazy() support fractional shares, rounds shares down to the nearest multiple of rounding. This has no effect on an LP() allocation.\nreinvest: if true, reinvests the money earned from short positions of the portfolio into buying more long positions.\nshort_ratio: long to short portfolio ratio, 0.2 corresponds to 120/20 long to short shares. If nothing defaults to portfolio weights.\noptimiser: only used for the LP() allocation. Needs to support mixed-interger linear programming.\nsilent: if true the optimiser is silent.\n\nExample\n\nef = EfficientFrontier(\n    tickers,\n    mean_ret,\n    cov_mtx;\n    market_neutral = true,\n    weight_bounds = (-1, 1),\n)\nmax_quadratic_utility!(ef)\n\n# Mixed integer, programming, no rounding available.\nallocLP, leftoverLP = Allocation(LP(), ef, latest_prices; investment = 3590)\n\n# Greedy allocation up to quarter shares.\nallocGreedy, leftoverGreedy = Allocation(Greedy(), ef, latest_prices; rounding = 0.25)\n\n# Lazy allocation with a 110/10 long-short ratio and reinvesting \n# earnings from selling the short positions into buying long positions.\nallocLazy, leftoverLazy = Allocation(\n                            Lazy(), ef, latest_prices; \n                            short_ratio = 0.1, reinvest = true\n                        )\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"api/#PortfolioOptimiser.roundmult","page":"API","title":"PortfolioOptimiser.roundmult","text":"roundmult(val, prec [, args...] [; kwargs...])\n\nRound a number to a multiple of prec. Uses the same defaults and has the same args and kwargs of the built-in Base.round.\n\nEquivalent to:\n\nround(div(val, prec) * prec, args...; kwargs...)\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"idx/#PortfolioOptimiser-API-Index","page":"Index","title":"PortfolioOptimiser API Index","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"idx/","page":"Index","title":"Index","text":"","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"Home","title":"Home","text":"CurrentModule = PortfolioOptimiser","category":"page"},{"location":"#PortfolioOptimiser","page":"Home","title":"PortfolioOptimiser","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"","page":"Home","title":"Home","text":"Documentation for PortfolioOptimiser.","category":"page"}]
